UNIT.learningOutcomes:
By the end of the sub-strand, the learner should be able to:
a) classify common substances found in the Kenyan environment as acids or bases based on their observable properties;
b) define acids and bases using the Arrhenius definition and write ionic equations showing H⁺ and OH⁻ ion production;
c) describe and write balanced chemical equations for the reactions of acids with metals, bases, metal carbonates, and metal hydrogen carbonates;
d) use commercial indicators and pH indicator paper to determine and compare the pH values of given solutions;
e) distinguish between strong and weak acids and bases in terms of degree of ionisation and relate this to their pH values;
f) explain the uses of acids and bases in everyday life, Kenyan agriculture (e.g., soil pH management in Kericho tea farms), and industry.
